00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:20.620
But, I never thought
about who invented it.

00:05:20.620 --> 00:05:22.840
Right? It's a strange
thing to think about.

00:05:22.840 --> 00:05:25.510
So, then I, then I tried to
imagine an alternate universe

00:05:25.510 --> 00:05:26.900
where the piano was never invented.

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:30.150
I thought about things like,
well, what would Beethoven's

00:05:30.150 --> 00:05:32.580
"Moonlight Sonata"
have sounded like,

00:05:32.580 --> 00:05:34.620
and how would it have
been delivered?

00:05:34.620 --> 00:05:37.800
I guess maybe by harpsichord
or a string quartet.

00:05:37.800 --> 00:05:41.180
But, then a [inaudible]
notion popped into my head.

00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:44.890
I said, "Would Beethoven
have invented it at all?"

00:05:44.890 --> 00:05:48.310
And, I think he would have,
but it was a striking question

00:05:48.310 --> 00:05:52.030 position:56%
that got right to the heart of an
interesting and more profound query.

00:05:52.030 --> 00:05:55.550
At what points in history did newly
invented instruments find their way

00:05:55.550 --> 00:05:59.250
into the hands of the
nominally talented musicians?

00:05:59.250 --> 00:06:04.100
How did musicians of Beethoven's
caliber react to a new instrument?

00:06:04.100 --> 00:06:06.660
How did Jimi Hendrix react
when he first got his hands

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:09.580
on a Fender Stratocaster?

00:06:09.580 --> 00:06:12.700
Where are these encounters in
history, and were the inventors

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:15.650
of musical instruments
musicians themselves?

00:06:15.650 --> 00:06:19.810
If we try to trace the evolution
of musical instruments back

00:06:19.810 --> 00:06:22.980
to their origins, we sometimes
lose the trail of where they come

00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:25.770
from and who invented them.

00:06:25.770 --> 00:06:29.190
The same thing happens
with music itself.

00:06:29.190 --> 00:06:32.910 position:56%
For all the tones written about
musical instruments in music theory,

00:06:32.910 --> 00:06:36.980
the origins of music are
still relatively unknown.

00:06:36.980 --> 00:06:41.010
Now, I imagined a bunch of
early homo sapiens listening

00:06:41.010 --> 00:06:45.380
to all the sounds of nature
and trying to imitate them.

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:48.360
After all, we still have
hunters using animal calls.

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:51.630
Except now, they aren't
required to perfect them vocally.

00:06:51.630 --> 00:06:54.480
They can just walk out in the
woods with a Bluetooth speaker,

00:06:54.480 --> 00:06:58.400
press play, hide, and
wait for the kill.

00:06:58.400 --> 00:06:59.940
Takes no talent.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:02.940
And, today, a talented
vocalist sells out stadiums,

00:07:02.940 --> 00:07:05.460
but maybe back then, a
talented vocalist could mimic

00:07:05.460 --> 00:07:07.830
and consistently attract prey.

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:14.370 position:56%
In the beginning, did music help,
did music evolve to help us survive,

00:07:14.370 --> 00:07:17.530
or was it a way to
communicate with gods?

00:07:18.620 --> 00:07:23.900
Hunting rituals, harvest
rituals, spiritual rituals,

00:07:23.900 --> 00:07:28.050
these are all possible explanations
for why music came to exist.

00:07:28.050 --> 00:07:31.410
But, in the end, no one
knows where music comes from.

00:07:31.410 --> 00:07:35.790
And, it turns out that the
historical relationship

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:40.440
between makers and musicians is
similarly difficult to trace,

00:07:40.440 --> 00:07:42.460
but there's one fantastic
example of a maker

00:07:42.460 --> 00:07:44.310
and musician who's virtuosity

00:07:44.310 --> 00:07:47.430
and inventiveness changed
the world of music forever.

00:07:48.660 --> 00:07:52.990
Pantaleon Hebenstreit was employed
as a violinist, keyboard musician,

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:55.680
and dance instructor in Leipzig.

00:07:55.680 --> 00:07:59.260
He constructed, developed, and
mastered a unique, enlarged version

00:07:59.260 --> 00:08:02.990
of the hammered dulcimer in 1697.

00:08:02.990 --> 00:08:06.680
In 1705, he traveled to
France, and created a sensation

00:08:06.680 --> 00:08:09.520
with his unique instrument
and playing.

00:08:09.520 --> 00:08:12.230
Louis XIV was so astonished
by his performance

00:08:12.230 --> 00:08:14.370
and the instrument
itself that he ordered it

00:08:14.370 --> 00:08:18.150
to be called the Pantaleon
from then on.

00:08:18.150 --> 00:08:20.230
This was quite an anomaly
at the time

00:08:20.230 --> 00:08:24.430
because the hammered keyboard
instruments were not nearly

00:08:24.430 --> 00:08:28.340
as popular as plucked
string keyboard instruments.

00:08:28.340 --> 00:08:32.240
The harpsichord enjoyed huge
popularity in the Baroque Period,

00:08:32.240 --> 00:08:37.500
but by 1709, an Italian harpsichord
maker named Bartolomeo Cristofori

00:08:37.500 --> 00:08:40.750
thought it was time to
update the harpsichord.

00:08:40.750 --> 00:08:42.450
He published a remarkable design

00:08:42.450 --> 00:08:46.290
of what eventually would
become the pianoforte.

00:08:46.290 --> 00:08:49.040
The keyboard design principle
was the same, but his series

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:53.130
of hammers striking the strings
rather than plucking them opened

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:55.130
up a whole new range
of possibilities

00:08:55.130 --> 00:08:57.930
for composers and performers.

00:08:57.930 --> 00:09:02.090 position:56%
This changed, this transformed music
performance and composition forever.

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:05.310
And, those conceived and
born in Italy, it was,

00:09:05.310 --> 00:09:09.220
the piano was developed over
the next four years in Germany.

00:09:09.220 --> 00:09:12.570
The famous organ builder
Gottfried Silbermann went

00:09:12.570 --> 00:09:15.520
through several iterations
of a grand piano with a vocal

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:20.880
and harsh critic named
Johann Sebastian Bach

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:22.720
who preferred his organs.

00:09:22.720 --> 00:09:26.790
Now, a remarkable innovation
to the piano

00:09:26.790 --> 00:09:30.440
by a maker named Johann Andreas
Stein caught the attention

00:09:30.440 --> 00:09:32.460
of another musical luminary.

00:09:32.460 --> 00:09:38.740 position:56%
In a letter to his father written in
1777, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart wrote,

00:09:38.740 --> 00:09:42.620
"His instruments distinguish
themselves by an escapement.

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:46.030
Not one in a hundred makers
troubles himself about that,

00:09:46.030 --> 00:09:50.320
but without an escapement, a
piano clatters and leaves a sound.

00:09:50.320 --> 00:09:54.680 position:56%
When one presses the keys, his
hammers fall down in the very moment

00:09:54.680 --> 00:09:57.030
in which they bounce
against the string,

00:09:57.030 --> 00:09:59.170
whether one holds the
key down or releases it."

00:09:59.170 --> 00:10:05.770
In 1821, Sebastian Erard invented
the double escapement action

00:10:05.770 --> 00:10:10.460
which incorporated a repetition
lever, also called a balancier,

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:13.610
that permitted repeating a note
even if the key had not yet risen

00:10:13.610 --> 00:10:16.150
to its maximum vertical position.

00:10:17.750 --> 00:10:21.400
This facilitated rapid
playing of repeated notes,

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:24.930
a musical device exploited
by Franz Liszt.

00:10:26.160 --> 00:10:29.790
When the invention became
public as revised by Henri Herz,

00:10:29.790 --> 00:10:32.150
the double escapement action
gradually became standard

00:10:32.150 --> 00:10:35.860
in grand pianos and
is still incorporated

00:10:35.860 --> 00:10:38.210
into all grand pianos
currently produced.

00:10:38.210 --> 00:10:42.300
Still, no one knows
where music comes from,

00:10:42.300 --> 00:10:46.240
but it is a clear example
of a musician

00:10:46.240 --> 00:10:49.530
who invented his own
instrument, performed on it,

00:10:49.530 --> 00:10:51.120
and inspired the creation of one

00:10:51.120 --> 00:10:56.380
of the most popular
instruments of all time.

