project with the Smithsonian.

00:29:21.610 --> 00:29:24.230
Needless to say, biggest
collection of museum in the world.

00:29:24.230 --> 00:29:28.320
90 museums, 137 million objects.

00:29:28.320 --> 00:29:30.290
Catastrophe, right?

00:29:30.290 --> 00:29:33.990 position:56%
And, for those of you who like going
to museum like me, you only see 2%

00:29:33.990 --> 00:29:35.430
because there is no space.

00:29:35.430 --> 00:29:38.180
You don't get enough buildings
here, so a lot of the stuff is

00:29:38.180 --> 00:29:42.600
in storage rooms, etc. And, a
very smart, young energized team

00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:45.540
in the Smithsonian decided there
must be a solution to this.

00:29:45.540 --> 00:29:48.570
How can we show the collections
that we have to the whole world,

00:29:48.570 --> 00:29:51.440
not only those who come
to museums and see 2%,

00:29:51.440 --> 00:29:53.270
but everything to everybody?

00:29:53.270 --> 00:29:55.530
And, thus, how to engage
the kids of today who think

00:29:55.530 --> 00:29:58.530
that computers are everything,
and they find that, you know,

00:29:58.530 --> 00:30:03.880
museums are kind of archaic
institutions, in their opinion.

00:30:03.880 --> 00:30:08.090
So, this team started
digitizing some iconic pieces

00:30:08.090 --> 00:30:11.190
from different museums,
and at that moment, we met.

00:30:11.190 --> 00:30:17.220
And we conceptualized together a
solution that will bring museums

00:30:17.220 --> 00:30:20.330
on the cloud, accessible
to everybody online.

00:30:20.330 --> 00:30:24.110
And, this was a prototype
that we together did.

00:30:24.110 --> 00:30:26.800
It's called the Smithsonian
X 3D in which we started

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:30.630
with about 20 iconic objects
from as small as a bit

00:30:30.630 --> 00:30:32.450
to as big as a supernova remnant.

00:30:32.450 --> 00:30:36.780
And, basically, the idea
was to put them in a browser

00:30:36.780 --> 00:30:40.840 position:56%
and let people explore it while also
following what the curators have

00:30:40.840 --> 00:30:44.020
spent their entire lives
with those artifacts can tell

00:30:44.020 --> 00:30:45.330
about those subjects.

00:30:45.330 --> 00:30:46.630
We have a couple of rules.

00:30:46.630 --> 00:30:50.110
We wanted the objects to be
as beautiful as in real life

00:30:50.110 --> 00:30:52.220
and not as in second life.

00:30:52.220 --> 00:30:55.830
Then, we wanted to offer some
tools that scientists can use,

00:30:55.830 --> 00:30:59.370
that curators can do for
researching, for comparing,

00:30:59.370 --> 00:31:03.090
for measuring, sectioning through.

00:31:03.090 --> 00:31:04.980
Some objects are more interesting

00:31:04.980 --> 00:31:07.160
with what's happening
inside that outside.

00:31:07.160 --> 00:31:11.840
Profiling, then allow curators
to define hot zones and hot spots

00:31:11.840 --> 00:31:16.170
to get additional explanation
and create tours on their own.

00:31:16.170 --> 00:31:19.780
So, here is a little video
that I made, but you're welcome

00:31:19.780 --> 00:31:21.080
to explore it on your own.

00:31:21.080 --> 00:31:22.870
It's called Smithsonian X 3D.

00:31:22.870 --> 00:31:26.570
This is one of the two life
masks from around Lincoln.

00:31:26.570 --> 00:31:29.020
As you can see, you
can change the setting.

00:31:29.020 --> 00:31:30.320
You can see it in 3D.

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:31.620
you can explore it.

00:31:31.620 --> 00:31:32.920
Imagine you're a teacher.

00:31:32.920 --> 00:31:34.220
You're teaching about the mammoth.

00:31:34.220 --> 00:31:36.650
Instead of saying, "Open
book on page 130," you say,

00:31:36.650 --> 00:31:40.660
"Download the Smithsonian digital
mammoth and tell me how big was it.

00:31:40.660 --> 00:31:42.150
How tall was his leg?"

00:31:42.150 --> 00:31:46.910
etc. And, but also we wanted to use
this artifacts to make some fun,

00:31:46.910 --> 00:31:50.600
to make art, for example, a sticker
for a t-shirt out of the mammoth,

00:31:50.600 --> 00:31:53.090
etc. This is my favorite project

00:31:53.090 --> 00:31:57.320
because this is a single cosmic
Buddha, unique in the world,

00:31:57.320 --> 00:32:00.750
and the relief was so shallow that
it was not possible to read it.

00:32:00.750 --> 00:32:02.680
When we showed the curator

00:32:02.680 --> 00:32:05.030
that he actually can make
the relief deeper just

00:32:05.030 --> 00:32:08.540
because it was digitized,
he was sold because this is

00:32:08.540 --> 00:32:12.370
where you see how technology today
can help you research a little bit

00:32:12.370 --> 00:32:16.340
deeper, a little bit different
and present and explain

00:32:16.340 --> 00:32:20.070
about our past achievements
or about details

00:32:20.070 --> 00:32:22.820
of our inventions in
a new, different way.

00:32:22.820 --> 00:32:25.390
Obviously, again, because
everything is in 3D,

00:32:25.390 --> 00:32:30.240 position:56%
researchers are using 3D printouts
in order not to touch the originals,

00:32:30.240 --> 00:32:32.490
but also using them for education.

00:32:32.490 --> 00:32:35.430
We even use some other software
that's not for 3D printing

00:32:35.430 --> 00:32:36.730
but for cardboard making.

00:32:36.730 --> 00:32:41.950
One to 3D make, to make one on one
crates for different objects just

00:32:41.950 --> 00:32:45.760
by making the negative of the
object and then making the crate.

00:32:45.760 --> 00:32:47.060
These, I personally made.

00:32:47.060 --> 00:32:51.620 position:56%
It was, it costed me about $70 and
three hours of my time versus couple

00:32:51.620 --> 00:32:54.550
of thousand dollars of a crate,
for shipping, and for archiving,

00:32:54.550 --> 00:33:00.990
etc. And, this is all possible with
this new ways of either digitizing

00:33:00.990 --> 00:33:02.980
or designing or making things.

00:33:02.980 --> 00:33:06.050
Smithsonian definitely paved the
path of the future of the museums,

00:33:06.050 --> 00:33:07.630 position:56%
the future of experience, the future

00:33:07.630 --> 00:33:11.050
of education, the future
of curation.

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:15.090
So, this all sounds very
simple and easy, but actually,

00:33:15.090 --> 00:33:17.380
when all of these pioneers
started to do that,

00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:21.180 position:56%
realizing the opportunities of the
technologies, it was very difficult.

00:33:21.180 --> 00:33:24.840
They had to learn super many
software that they, as curators

00:33:24.840 --> 00:33:27.130
or scientists, was like,
I'm not mechanical engineer.

00:33:27.130 --> 00:33:28.480
I cannot use this.

00:33:28.480 --> 00:33:30.720
it was a very difficult
process and very complex.

00:33:30.720 --> 00:33:34.700
These led us to the idea by
working with these people

00:33:34.700 --> 00:33:38.670
who knew what they wanted to create
a product that we call Momento

00:33:38.670 --> 00:33:43.140
that basically enables you, either
from photos or from laser scans

00:33:43.140 --> 00:33:45.690
or structuralized scanners,
in the most easy way.

00:33:45.690 --> 00:33:46.990
This is shown with photos.

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:48.960
You just take bunch of photos.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:53.600
You load them in the software, and
then the software converts them

00:33:53.600 --> 00:33:56.080
into a 3D digital replica.

00:33:56.080 --> 00:33:59.180
At first, when you receive it,
you receive something like this,

00:33:59.180 --> 00:34:00.790
and you say, wait a second.

00:34:00.790 --> 00:34:03.620
I took photos of the
sculpture, and I got that mess.

00:34:03.620 --> 00:34:05.260
But, actually, the
sculpture is in the middle.

00:34:05.260 --> 00:34:07.840
Obviously, the photos did
not know how far to go,

00:34:07.840 --> 00:34:09.230
so they were just capturing
everything.

00:34:09.230 --> 00:34:12.200
But, then we made bunch of
[inaudible] really easily.

00:34:12.200 --> 00:34:15.760
Clean up the environment, then
close the holes if you wanted to.

00:34:15.760 --> 00:34:21.110 position:56%
You print it to be, so it's like a
3D photoshop, making 3D photography.

00:34:21.110 --> 00:34:25.120
But then, that photography can be
turned into the real world back

00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:31.190
to CNC, to 3D printing, etc.
So, why does this matter to you,

00:34:31.190 --> 00:34:35.940 position:56%
and how does this relate to anything
that you came for here tonight?

00:34:35.940 --> 00:34:41.320
Well, all of these pioneers have
recognized new opportunities opened

00:34:41.320 --> 00:34:42.620
with advanced technology.

00:34:42.620 --> 00:34:44.710
In particular, with
the following trends.

00:34:44.710 --> 00:34:49.240
The trends of ubiquitous
sensors, the trends of new ways

00:34:49.240 --> 00:34:52.140
to fabrication, to
CNC, to 3D printing,

00:34:52.140 --> 00:34:56.590
and trends of the powerful 3D web
and augmented through anything,

00:34:56.590 --> 00:35:00.360
mixed reality, smart
mobiles, etc. So,

00:35:00.360 --> 00:35:02.350
what do I mean by ubiquitous
sensors?

00:35:02.350 --> 00:35:05.100
Well, we're live in
an age of sensors.

00:35:05.100 --> 00:35:08.720
Sensors are any photo camera
on your phone, on your iPad,

00:35:08.720 --> 00:35:10.700
on your pocket camera, big camera.

00:35:10.700 --> 00:35:13.120
Something that used to cost
couple of thousand dollar camera,

00:35:13.120 --> 00:35:15.580
now that quality sensor,
you have it on every phone

00:35:15.580 --> 00:35:18.050 position:56%
that you guys have here in the room.

00:35:18.050 --> 00:35:19.460
But, there are also
other types of sensors.

00:35:19.460 --> 00:35:21.890
There is something that
we call structure light

00:35:21.890 --> 00:35:25.740
which is basically photo with a
projector, and then laser scanners.

00:35:25.740 --> 00:35:29.990
They vary in price and, but
they all have the same trend.

00:35:29.990 --> 00:35:32.130
They become cheaper and better.

00:35:32.130 --> 00:35:33.430
So, they become ubiquitous.

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:35.090
They become accessible.

00:35:35.090 --> 00:35:38.200
The second trend is about
the new way of making things,

00:35:38.200 --> 00:35:39.820
the new fabrication methods.

00:35:39.820 --> 00:35:41.610
For a long time now,

00:35:41.610 --> 00:35:45.200
digital fabrication methods
have exchanged the analog method

00:35:45.200 --> 00:35:49.660
of cutting and chopping, etc. We
have now what we call CNC machines,

00:35:49.660 --> 00:35:52.500
Computer Numerically
Controlled machines

00:35:52.500 --> 00:35:55.790
that usually require a digital
file to make something awesome.

00:35:55.790 --> 00:35:58.780
And, the one that is most famous
is obviously the additive one,

00:35:58.780 --> 00:36:00.180
the 3D printers.

00:36:00.180 --> 00:36:03.450
And 3D printers are not interesting
because hey you can buy them

00:36:03.450 --> 00:36:05.440
and put them at home
and make, you know,

00:36:05.440 --> 00:36:08.780
plastic ducks and iPhone covers.

00:36:08.780 --> 00:36:10.670
How many of those can we make?

00:36:10.670 --> 00:36:12.450
But, it's more interesting

00:36:12.450 --> 00:36:16.040
because you don't need
knowledge to use them.

00:36:16.040 --> 00:36:17.430
They're affordable.

00:36:17.430 --> 00:36:20.000
They allow for distributive
manufacturing,

00:36:20.000 --> 00:36:23.480
meaning that they can be in
many places in the world,

00:36:23.480 --> 00:36:25.040
and instead of I design something.

00:36:25.040 --> 00:36:26.340
I want to make it.

00:36:26.340 --> 00:36:29.350
I have to order it from China,
from America, from wherever.

00:36:29.350 --> 00:36:30.760
It can be locally made.

00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:33.220
But, most interestingly about
all the different effects

00:36:33.220 --> 00:36:36.620
in 3D printing is that
complexity comes for free.

00:36:36.620 --> 00:36:40.190
A printer does not care
if you're printing a box

00:36:40.190 --> 00:36:42.780
or if you're printing
something super beautiful,

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:45.650
just like what you will
see later being done.

00:36:45.650 --> 00:36:48.590
And, this, now, leads us to
the effect that to understand

00:36:48.590 --> 00:36:51.020
that until now, we
have been designing

00:36:51.020 --> 00:36:54.080
for subtractive manufacturing
method.

00:36:54.080 --> 00:36:57.970
Now, we have the opportunity
to revisit how we design things

00:36:57.970 --> 00:37:01.680
and to start, maybe, designing with
algorithms and leveraging the fact

00:37:01.680 --> 00:37:05.570
that this 3D printers can
print very complex structures.

00:37:05.570 --> 00:37:09.850
So, something like a bike
stand can be much, much lighter

00:37:09.850 --> 00:37:12.930
and much sturdier if it is make
out of [inaudible] structure,

00:37:12.930 --> 00:37:15.080
but that was not possible
to be done until now

00:37:15.080 --> 00:37:17.370
in the ways we were manufacturing.

00:37:17.370 --> 00:37:21.060
This has a huge impact
on the world of design.

00:37:21.060 --> 00:37:24.910
And, the last trend that
I spoke of is the 3D web,

00:37:24.910 --> 00:37:30.170
the web go technologies, the
oculus rifts in Microsoft Lenses,

00:37:30.170 --> 00:37:35.760
and all of these new ways allow
us to experience in a new way.

00:37:35.760 --> 00:37:41.090
So, to conclude, scientists,
researchers, curators, doctors,

00:37:41.090 --> 00:37:43.860
designers, artists of all kinds,

00:37:43.860 --> 00:37:46.440
they will have much
more fun in the future.

00:37:46.440 --> 00:37:50.100
They will be able to push
their professions to new limits

00:37:50.100 --> 00:37:55.250
that they never thought they
could do, and this concept

00:37:55.250 --> 00:37:58.610
of which we call rip, fix, burn.

00:37:58.610 --> 00:37:59.910
Rip the reality.

00:37:59.910 --> 00:38:03.720
Fix it, mix it, change it, and then
reburn it back with 3D printing

00:38:03.720 --> 00:38:05.990
or CNC or rip, fix, learn.

00:38:05.990 --> 00:38:07.460
Educate in a new way.

00:38:07.460 --> 00:38:08.760
Teach in a new way.

00:38:08.760 --> 00:38:10.060
Experience in a new way.

00:38:10.060 --> 00:38:13.350
I believe will affect
every aspect of our lives.

00:38:13.350 --> 00:38:15.150
Thank you so much.

