00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:26.750
And, I've been using CT to look

00:42:26.750 --> 00:42:29.590
at the fine details of
woodwind manufacture.

00:42:29.590 --> 00:42:34.250 position:56%
Micro CT, that is to say CT with
pixel sizes in the micrometer range,

00:42:34.250 --> 00:42:37.190
1/1000 of a millimeter, allows us

00:42:37.190 --> 00:42:39.590
to study objects with
extreme precision.

00:42:39.590 --> 00:42:43.430
And, of course, any CT allows us
to view the anatomy of an object

00:42:43.430 --> 00:42:46.550
from any point of view
without taking measurements

00:42:46.550 --> 00:42:49.380
and without doing anything that
might damage the instruments.

00:42:49.380 --> 00:42:51.300
And, just to clarify for everyone,

00:42:51.300 --> 00:42:52.860
what's the difference
between x-ray and CT?

00:42:52.860 --> 00:42:57.120
The gentleman on the left is
being subject to an x-ray.

00:42:57.120 --> 00:43:01.090
There's a plate behind him
and a beam is going to go

00:43:01.090 --> 00:43:03.370
through his chest and
expose the plate.

00:43:03.370 --> 00:43:10.130
It's instantaneous, but it only
gives you a 2D object, oh, 2D view.

00:43:10.130 --> 00:43:14.300
The woman on the right who's
going to be subject to a CT,

00:43:14.300 --> 00:43:17.930
that torus has beams, has
beams that are going to come

00:43:17.930 --> 00:43:19.770
from all directions around her,

00:43:19.770 --> 00:43:21.910
and then there are
detectors on the other side.

00:43:21.910 --> 00:43:28.890 position:56%
So, just as you were displaying here
with the cameras, we'll get a myriad

00:43:28.890 --> 00:43:33.090
of views which are then summed by
the computer to create a 3D file

00:43:33.090 --> 00:43:36.850
that can be viewed from
any desired object.

00:43:36.850 --> 00:43:42.330 position:56%
So, to do the work on the saxophone,
I needed an expert in micro CT,

00:43:42.330 --> 00:43:47.880 position:56%
and I was fortunate to find Dr. Sina
Shahbazmohamadi who is the director,

00:43:47.880 --> 00:43:51.700
now, if imaging at the Chase Labs
at University of Connecticut.

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:56.710
And, my advisor, Richard Bass,
helped out also from musicological

00:43:56.710 --> 00:43:58.740
and administrative points of view.

00:43:58.740 --> 00:44:00.900
Then, we were very,
we are very fortunate

00:44:00.900 --> 00:44:02.520
that Sina's wife Zahra
[assumed spelling],

00:44:02.520 --> 00:44:05.810
who is also a mechanical engineer,
was able to become our consultant

00:44:05.810 --> 00:44:07.540
for additive manufacture.

00:44:07.540 --> 00:44:10.100
We did some initial work on
the instruments that Richard

00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:13.710
and I are holding, the curved
English horn and the recorder,

00:44:13.710 --> 00:44:17.140 position:56%
and then you can see that Dr.
Shahbazmohamadi is holding the tenor

00:44:17.140 --> 00:44:21.930
saxophone in question with one
of our replicated mouthpieces.

00:44:21.930 --> 00:44:24.430
In his, in his micro CT work,

00:44:24.430 --> 00:44:28.350
Sina used the standard industrial
equipment at two labs a UConn,

00:44:28.350 --> 00:44:30.440
and he performed our
data manipulation.

00:44:30.440 --> 00:44:33.880
Here to show you how
that's done on the right.

00:44:33.880 --> 00:44:37.600
On the leftmost part of the
image, there's the x-ray source.

00:44:37.600 --> 00:44:41.560
Then, in the middle, that
orange yellow thing is the tie

00:44:41.560 --> 00:44:44.130
on an oboe reed, and
it's in a holder

00:44:44.130 --> 00:44:48.050
which will rotate 1/1000th
of a circle.

00:44:48.050 --> 00:44:49.910
Then, the ten second
exposure's taken.

00:44:49.910 --> 00:44:54.020
Then, it moves 1/1000th of a circle
so as to get that myriad of views

00:44:54.020 --> 00:44:56.410
that we need for the CT analysis.

00:44:56.410 --> 00:44:59.780
And then, the detector
is on the far right.

00:45:01.480 --> 00:45:04.880
Sina and I were, then,
able to do manipulation

00:45:04.880 --> 00:45:07.500
and clarification of the data.

00:45:07.500 --> 00:45:10.040
We benefitted very much
from the advantages

00:45:10.040 --> 00:45:15.210
of micro computed tomography,
and the last one, of course,

00:45:15.210 --> 00:45:18.370
the last two are the ones that are
of substantial importance to us

00:45:18.370 --> 00:45:19.830
in a saxophone mouthpiece.

00:45:19.830 --> 00:45:23.680
The internal geometry is
notoriously difficult to measure,

00:45:23.680 --> 00:45:25.800
and we could translate
it into some form

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:30.510
for added manufacture
of computerized milling.

00:45:30.510 --> 00:45:35.340
The disadvantages of micro CT,
however are not, are not trivial.

00:45:35.340 --> 00:45:37.930
The greatest one being
the limited specimen size.

00:45:37.930 --> 00:45:40.800
The largest specimen that
our machine can handle is ten

00:45:40.800 --> 00:45:44.680
centimeters in dimension, so we
are obliged, for something as small

00:45:44.680 --> 00:45:48.330
as a saxophone mouthpiece,
to take two views and then

00:45:48.330 --> 00:45:52.880
to stitch them digitally.

00:45:52.880 --> 00:45:54.180
Y'all should take this for granted.

00:45:54.180 --> 00:45:56.260
Here's how additive
manufacture works.

00:45:56.260 --> 00:45:58.340
You take a CAD file.

00:45:58.340 --> 00:46:02.830 position:56%
You create another file out of
that, and you lay it down in layers.

00:46:02.830 --> 00:46:05.620
It's the creation of an object by
applying thin layer of material,

00:46:05.620 --> 00:46:07.150
one atop the other, rather

00:46:07.150 --> 00:46:09.850
than removing material
from a larger block.

00:46:09.850 --> 00:46:12.790
So, instead of taking a piece
of stone and removing everything

00:46:12.790 --> 00:46:15.390
that doesn't look like a
bunny, you take nothing

00:46:15.390 --> 00:46:18.020
and you add all the stuff
that does look like a bunny,

00:46:18.020 --> 00:46:19.640
and you end up with a bunny.

00:46:19.640 --> 00:46:22.760
But, the important thing's that
it permits extreme precision

00:46:22.760 --> 00:46:26.630
and unlimited numbers of copies.

00:46:27.650 --> 00:46:31.150
This is, this is a
low complexity machine

00:46:31.150 --> 00:46:35.050
at work, probably making a bunny.

00:46:35.050 --> 00:46:38.920
So, here's the foot joint on
the left of an antique recorder

00:46:38.920 --> 00:46:42.770
by Cahuzac [assumed spelling] circa
1750, and then there's a copy made

00:46:42.770 --> 00:46:44.920
by a professional recorder maker,

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:48.090
and then there's four identical
copies that Sina and I made.

00:46:48.090 --> 00:46:50.140
My daughter, Katherine, is
