00:47:31.100 --> 00:47:34.050
by a professional recorder maker.

00:47:34.050 --> 00:47:40.610 position:56%
And, he also demonstrated, by taking
CTs of our copies and comparing them

00:47:40.610 --> 00:47:45.670
to CTs of the original and of the
artisan copy, that the dimensions

00:47:45.670 --> 00:47:49.740
that are hardest to
take by a craftsman,

00:47:49.740 --> 00:47:51.980
particularly the internal
diameters of tone holes

00:47:51.980 --> 00:47:54.810
where you're measuring
at a deep level.

00:47:54.810 --> 00:47:57.700
Those showed the greatest
advantage for micro CT.

00:47:57.700 --> 00:48:03.730
So, the method had an error of
less than 1% in all dimensions.

00:48:03.730 --> 00:48:07.990
It was within the error
of my measurements.

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:11.560
So, here's the anatomy of
a saxophone mouthpiece,

00:48:11.560 --> 00:48:14.030
and look particularly at
the upper one on the left.

00:48:14.030 --> 00:48:15.640
It shows the tip opening.

00:48:15.640 --> 00:48:17.930
That's the place where the air goes

00:48:17.930 --> 00:48:21.520
through between the
reed and the mouthpiece.

00:48:21.520 --> 00:48:25.180
And, the reed has its excursion
between this position you see

00:48:25.180 --> 00:48:26.740
and the tip of the mouthpiece.

00:48:26.740 --> 00:48:28.520
If the reed is too soft,

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:32.480
