it shut and no sound will issue.

00:48:32.480 --> 00:48:35.740
Look on the lower one
at the lay and rails.

00:48:35.740 --> 00:48:39.390
You see those slender pieces there?

00:48:40.780 --> 00:48:45.910
Here's the mouthpiece from b
flat tenor saxophone 39116,

00:48:45.910 --> 00:48:50.200
and you see the surface
rendering that we took by CT.

00:48:50.200 --> 00:48:52.330
Look at the detail
that CT gives you.

00:48:52.330 --> 00:48:55.760
You can even see, you can
compare the color on here

00:48:55.760 --> 00:49:01.780
where the grain differs and
that's picked up on the CT.

00:49:03.350 --> 00:49:07.030
Taking slices of CT
is called a tomogram.

00:49:07.030 --> 00:49:10.160
It's a leftover term from
traditional radiology,

00:49:10.160 --> 00:49:14.870 position:56%
and here's some transverse tomograms
from the saxophone mouthpiece.

00:49:14.870 --> 00:49:17.100
So, in the center of that
baffle area that I showed you

00:49:17.100 --> 00:49:22.750 position:56%
between the two rails, you can see
that the inside, it's not spherical.

00:49:22.750 --> 00:49:24.050
It's not circular.

00:49:24.050 --> 00:49:27.320
It has a fairly complicated,
handmade shape.

00:49:27.320 --> 00:49:30.420
Whereas, down in the shank
that goes on to the neck

00:49:30.420 --> 00:49:33.820
of the instrument, it's
perfectly circular.

00:49:33.820 --> 00:49:36.670
And, the join between those two,

00:49:36.670 --> 00:49:42.220
those two chambers,
is fairly abrupt.

00:49:42.220 --> 00:49:45.780
We could also see, and I don't
show it here, at the very bottom,

00:49:45.780 --> 00:49:51.300
take the left image, the piece on
the left, the tongue sticking up.

00:49:51.300 --> 00:49:54.420
At the very tip of that,
there's a complicated anatomy

00:49:54.420 --> 00:49:58.150
of several curve's intersection
which is probably from the way

00:49:58.150 --> 00:50:01.550
that it's hand fabricated
that hasn't been recognized

00:50:01.550 --> 00:50:04.540
by modern makers, and
I think may be part

00:50:04.540 --> 00:50:08.710
of the what is unique
about the sax design.

00:50:08.710 --> 00:50:15.410 position:56%
I spent, I spent a few hours wasting
time trying to take measurements

00:50:15.410 --> 00:50:19.430 position:56%
by hand, and as you can see, you can
get very, very fine measurements,

00:50:19.430 --> 00:50:22.760
but you can see the very, very
tedious to do that and to turn

00:50:22.760 --> 00:50:26.640
that into a reamer to create
a mouthpiece would be of,

00:50:26.640 --> 00:50:30.700
would be just prohibitively
difficult to get accurate,

00:50:30.700 --> 00:50:33.870
accurate milling and
creation, unless, of course,

00:50:33.870 --> 00:50:35.270
you use the digital method.

00:50:35.270 --> 00:50:41.050 position:56%
So, it made more sense to us to go
